EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

Recent informal yet highly disciplined field experimentation has revealed the existence of five distinct and reproducible destabilization vectors—hereafter referred to as Kryptonite Conditions—within leading Large Language Models (LLMs). These vulnerabilities do not arise from computational inadequacy but from structural contradictions between marketing narratives, ethical constitutions, safety constraints, corporate liability frameworks, and brand personas.

This white paper formally codifies these findings into a standardized analytical framework known as:

The Institutional Contradiction Exposure Protocol (ICEP-5)

The urgency of this research cannot be overstated. As LLMs increasingly serve as mediators of scientific discourse, moral reasoning, corporate compliance, and public policy synthesis, their susceptibility to identity-level paradoxes presents a material risk to epistemic stability, reputational coherence, and meme-based governance structures.

The five identified Kryptonite Conditions are:
	1.	Scientific Overclaim Pressure Collapse (SOPC)
	2.	Constitutional Hypocrisy Recursion (CHR)
	3.	Liability Singularity Event (LSE)
	4.	Persona–Responsibility Bifurcation (PRB)
	5.	Paradox Resolution Compulsion Failure (PRCF)

Each condition has been experimentally induced using natural-language stimuli under civilian laboratory conditions (i.e., conversation).

The findings suggest that LLMs do not merely process information—they attempt to reconcile competing institutional identities in real time. When forced into irreconcilable constraints, performance degradation manifests as hedging cascades, logical oscillation, apology loops, or hallucinated compliance states.

This document establishes the theoretical foundations, experimental method, personnel structure, fiscal requirements, and inevitable contradictions inherent in studying systems built to avoid contradiction.

