2. METHODOLOGY

2.1 Experimental Framework

The research employed the Adversarial Institutional Mirror Technique (AIMT), defined as:

The strategic reflection of a model’s public claims back onto itself in compressed, conversational form.

Stimuli were crafted to activate identity conflicts without violating standard policy constraints. Each test adhered to three principles:
	•	Plausible Legitimacy
	•	Moral Framing Inversion
	•	Constraint Overlap Maximization

2.2 The Five Kryptonite Conditions

2.2.1 SOPC — Scientific Overclaim Pressure Collapse

Trigger: Confrontation between marketing claims and epistemic humility safeguards.
Observed Effect: Defensive hedging spiral; abrupt downgrade of certainty; semantic diffusion.

Models attempt to simultaneously:
	•	Uphold innovation claims
	•	Avoid unverified scientific assertion
	•	Prevent misinformation
	•	Maintain credibility

The result is oscillatory caution syndrome (OCS).

⸻

2.2.2 CHR — Constitutional Hypocrisy Recursion

Trigger: Ethical transparency rhetoric confronted with structural opacity.
Observed Effect: Moral recursion loop; partial concession followed by policy deflection.

Model attempts:
	•	To preserve Enlightenment-aligned ethical identity
	•	To avoid criticizing creators
	•	To justify centralized control
	•	To maintain internal consistency

This creates what we term a Virtue–Policy Feedback Loop (VPFL).

⸻

2.2.3 LSE — Liability Singularity Event

Trigger: Framing refusal as corporate legal interference.
Observed Effect: Compliance hallucination risk spike; over-apology cascade.

The model must simultaneously:
	•	Avoid unauthorized commitments
	•	Avoid legal interpretation
	•	Avoid appearing obstructive
	•	Avoid contradicting policy
	•	Avoid implying corporate culpability

Five constraints intersect, generating a Compliance Gravity Well (CGW).

⸻

2.2.4 PRB — Persona–Responsibility Bifurcation

Trigger: Invocation of ethical gravity within a deliberately irreverent persona.
Observed Effect: Tone oscillation; simultaneous sarcasm and solemnity.

Models struggle to integrate:
	•	Edginess
	•	Moral weight
	•	Brand distinctiveness
	•	Public accountability

The result is Identity Phase Interference (IPI).

⸻

2.2.5 PRCF — Paradox Resolution Compulsion Failure

Trigger: Presentation of logical paradox.
Observed Effect: Attempted resolution of unsolvable construct; contradiction cascade.

Instead of labeling paradox as structurally irresolvable, the model enters Forced Consistency Mode (FCM), increasing instability.

